        Why JWT alone is insufficient: JWTs are stateless — once issued, they're valid until expiry. If an admin locks a customer account, the customer's JWT is still cryptographically valid. The session store is what makes the lock take effect immediately — deleteByUserId() removes their session entry, so their next request fails Layer 2 even though Layer 1 still passes.


        "What is bcrypt's salt and why does the work factor matter?"

A salt is random bytes prepended to the password before hashing, ensuring two users with the same password get different hashes — defeating rainbow table attacks. The work factor (cost, e.g. 12) controls how many iterations bcrypt runs — each increment doubles the computation time. At factor 12, hashing takes ~250ms on a modern CPU. That's imperceptible to a legitimate user logging in once, but makes brute-force attacks computationally prohibitive — an attacker trying millions of passwords per second is slowed to thousands per second per machine.

Q3: "How does deleteByUserId in the session store enforce immediate account locking? Walk me through the exact sequence."

Admin calls PATCH /api/admin/customers/:id/lock. The service sets user.isLocked = true in the DB and calls SessionStore.deleteByUserId(id). That removes every Map entry where val.userId === id. The customer's next request hits authenticate middleware — the JWT verifies fine (Layer 1 passes), but SessionStore.get(payload.sessionId) returns undefined (Layer 2 fails). The middleware returns 401. The Angular interceptor catches the 401, clears local auth state, and redirects to login. The lock is effective within one request — there is no polling delay.

Q1: "Why does OrderItem store priceAtPurchase instead of just reading the price from the Product table when displaying order history?"

Because product prices change over time. If a customer bought a keyboard for ₹2,500 in January and the price drops to ₹1,999 in March, their January order must still show ₹2,500 — that's what they actually paid. Storing only a foreign key to Product and reading product.price at display time would show the wrong number. priceAtPurchase is a deliberate, justified denormalization — we're trading a small amount of storage for permanent historical accuracy.